################################################################################
#                                                                              #
#                      tomoauto installation instructions                      #
#                                                                              #
#------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
# AUTHOR: Dustin Reed Morado                                                   #
# VERSION: 0.2.30                                                              #
# DATE: 02.11.2015                                                             #
################################################################################

-- Preferably you can use git to copy the tomoauto repository to your system,
   which allows you to quickly update to the newest version or make changes and
   contribute bug-fixes very easily.

1. Change into the directory you want to install tomoauto.
   - e.g. cd ~/opt

2. Clone the tomoauto git repository from GitHub:
   - e.g. git clone https://github.com/DustinMorado/tomoauto.git

3. Change into the tomoauto directory.
   - e.g. cd ~/opt/tomoauto

4. Execute the install_tomoauto.sh script and follow the prompts.
   - e.g. ./install_tomoauto.sh

5. To use tomoauto first source the resulting tomoauto_init shell script
   - e.g. source ~/opt/tomoauto/tomoauto_init.zsh

6. [Optional] If you want access to tomoauto at startup add step 4 to your
   approriate shell startup file.
   - e.g. echo source ~/opt/tomoauto/tomoauto_init.zsh >> ~/.zshrc

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

-- If you downloaded a zip release from GitHub then:

1. Unzip the tomoauto directory to the location you want it to be installed.
   - e.g. cd ~/opt && unzip ~/Downloads/tomoauto.zip

2. Change into the tomoauto directory.
   - e.g. cd ~/opt/tomoauto

3. Execute the install_tomoauto.sh script and follow the prompts.
   - e.g. ./install_tomoauto.sh

4. To use tomoauto first source the resulting tomoauto_init shell script
   - e.g. source ~/opt/tomoauto/tomoauto_init.zsh

5. [Optional] If you want access to tomoauto at startup add step 4 to your
   approriate shell startup file.
   - e.g. echo source ~/opt/tomoauto/tomoauto_init.zsh >> ~/.zshrc
